As suggested in the hint we first add two trivial equations to help us
rewrite the recursion relation in matrix form:

\begin{alignat*}{7}
x_{n+3} &&\; = \;&& x_{n+2}             &&\; + \;&& x_{n+1}  &&\; + \;&& x_n & \\
x_{n+2} &&\; = \;&& x_{n+2}             &&\; \;&& &&\; \;&& & \\
x_{n+1} &&\; = \;&&  &&\; \;&& x_{n+1}  &&\; \;&& &
\end{alignat*}

This can be written as:

\[\begin{bmatrix}
x_{n+3}\\ 
x_{n+2}\\ 
x_{n+1}
\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
1 &1 &1 \\ 
1& 0 &0 \\ 
0& 1 &0 
\end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}
x_{n+2}\\ 
x_{n+1}\\ 
x_{n}
\end{bmatrix}\]

So define $A = \begin{bmatrix}
1 &1 &1 \\ 
1 & 1 &0 \\ 
0 & 0 &0 
\end{bmatrix}$ and $X_{n} = \begin{bmatrix}
x_{n+2}\\ x_{n+1}\\ x_{n}
\end{bmatrix}$. Plugging in \emph{n = 0} we see that the initial vector
\emph{X\textsubscript{0}} contains the initial
conditions\[X_{0} = \begin{bmatrix}
c\\ 
b\\ 
a
\end{bmatrix}.\]
